### 3.3 Prometheus

> [!info] What it is
> Prometheus is an open-source monitoring system and time-series database. Pull-based — Prometheus scrapes metrics from configured endpoints at regular intervals.

**Why Prometheus:**
- De facto standard for metrics in cloud-native environments
- Pull model is reliable (servers expose `/metrics`, Prometheus scrapes)
- PromQL query language is powerful
- Native Grafana integration

**Metrics typically collected:**
- CPU usage
- Memory usage
- Disk I/O
- Network traffic
- Application-specific metrics (request rate, errors, latency)

**Key Prometheus concepts:**
- **Targets** — endpoints to scrape
- **Scrape interval** — how often to pull (e.g., every 15 seconds)
- **Metrics types** — counter, gauge, histogram, summary
- **PromQL** — query language: `rate(http_requests_total[5m])`

**Interview prep:**
- *"Pull vs push model?"* → Pull is more reliable in distributed systems. Targets just expose metrics; Prometheus controls timing. Push works better for short-lived jobs
- *"What is PromQL?"* → Prometheus Query Language. Used to query metrics over time. E.g., `rate(http_requests_total[5m])` gives request rate
- *"Counters vs gauges?"* → Counter: monotonically increasing (total requests). Gauge: can go up or down (current memory). Histograms and summaries are for distributions

---

### 3.4 Loki

> [!info] What it is
> Grafana Loki — an open-source log aggregation system inspired by Prometheus. Designed to be cost-effective and scalable. Indexes labels rather than full log content.

**Why Loki (the "L" in the LGTM stack):**
- Designed by Grafana Labs (same family as Grafana, Prometheus, Tempo, Mimir)
- More cost-effective than ELK (Elasticsearch) — indexes only labels, not full text
- Native Grafana integration
- Uses LogQL (similar to PromQL)

**How Loki works:**
- Log shippers (Promtail, Fluentd, Vector) push logs from servers to Loki
- Logs are stored with labels (e.g., `server=prod1`, `service=api`)
- Loki indexes labels (cheap), not content (expensive)
- LogQL queries labels, then full-text searches matching log entries

**LogQL examples:**
- `{server="prod1"}` — all logs from server prod1
- `{severity="error"}` — all error logs
- `{server="prod1"} |= "exception"` — prod1 logs containing "exception"

**Interview prep:**
- *"Why Loki over ELK?"* → Cost — Loki indexes labels only, not full content, much cheaper at scale. ELK indexes everything, faster search but expensive
- *"How does Loki integrate with Grafana?"* → Native data source. You query LogQL in Grafana, see logs alongside metrics in the same dashboard

