## 🎓 PART 4 — Key Concepts to Master

### 4.1 Observability — The Three Pillars

1. **Logs** — discrete events (errors, requests, user actions)
2. **Metrics** — numerical measurements over time (CPU, latency, request rate)
3. **Traces** — end-to-end request flows through distributed systems

Your project covered logs (Loki) and metrics (Prometheus + SQL Server). Tracing (Tempo, Jaeger) is the third pillar.

### 4.2 Push vs Pull Monitoring

**Push model:**
- Services send metrics to a collector
- Better for short-lived jobs (batch, lambdas)
- Examples: StatsD, OpenTelemetry push

**Pull model:**
- Collector scrapes metrics from services at intervals
- Better for long-running services
- More reliable (no lost data if collector is down)
- Examples: Prometheus

### 4.3 Time-Series Data

Logs and metrics are time-series — values indexed by time.

**Time-series databases (TSDBs):**
- Prometheus (metrics)
- InfluxDB
- TimescaleDB
- VictoriaMetrics

Designed for high-write, append-only data with time-based queries.

### 4.4 Alerting Best Practices

**SLO-based alerting:**
- Define Service Level Objectives (e.g., 99.9% uptime)
- Alert when burn rate threatens the SLO

**Avoid alert fatigue:**
- Only alert on actionable issues
- Group related alerts
- Severity levels (info, warning, critical)
- Use silencing during maintenance

**Common alert patterns:**
- Threshold (CPU > 90%)
- Rate of change (error rate spike)
- Anomaly detection (deviation from baseline)
- Missing data (service stopped reporting)

### 4.5 Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) for Dashboards

In Grafana:
- Users / teams have roles (Viewer, Editor, Admin)
- Dashboards can be assigned to teams
- Folders organize dashboards by role
- Plant engineers can see plant dashboards; managers see KPI dashboards

### 4.6 Log Aggregation Patterns

**Sidecar pattern:**
- Log shipper runs alongside the service
- Reads service logs, ships to central store

**Logging agent:**
- Single agent per server (Filebeat, Promtail, Fluentd)
- Tails log files, ships to central store

**Library integration:**
- Service logs directly to central store via library
- Less common, more coupling

### 4.7 Common Logging Levels

- **DEBUG** — verbose, for development
- **INFO** — normal events
- **WARN** — something unusual, not an error
- **ERROR** — failure, needs attention
- **FATAL** — system crashing

