## 🎤 PART 5 — Common Interview Questions

### Q1: Walk me through the ITC log monitoring project

> At ITC Limited during my software development internship, I built a real-time log monitoring solution to replace manual log inspection across 5+ production servers. The system aggregates logs centrally, provides role-based dashboards, and alerts on critical events.
>
> Architecture-wise, logs flow from production servers to Loki for centralized storage. Prometheus scrapes server metrics in parallel. Structured events go into SQL Server. Grafana sits on top of all three as the visualization and alerting layer.
>
> I built role-based dashboards — plant engineers see server health and operational details for their assigned plants, while managers see KPIs and cross-plant summaries. Used Grafana dashboard variables to enable plant-specific filtering without duplicating dashboards. Set up alerts for critical system events. The end result reduced manual log inspection effort significantly for the ops team.

### Q2: What's the LGTM stack?

> Grafana's observability stack — Loki for logs, Grafana for visualization, Tempo for distributed tracing, and Mimir for scalable metrics storage. I used Loki and Grafana in this project. Prometheus served the metrics role (Mimir is essentially scaled Prometheus). It's the open-source alternative to commercial observability platforms like Datadog or New Relic.

### Q3: Why Prometheus for metrics?

> Three reasons. First, it's the industry standard for cloud-native monitoring — strong community, lots of integrations. Second, the pull model is more reliable for long-running services — Prometheus scrapes at consistent intervals; no risk of services pushing data and losing it. Third, PromQL is a powerful query language for time-series data — much better than SQL for things like rates and aggregations over time windows.

### Q4: Why Loki over Elasticsearch?

> Loki indexes only labels, not full log content. This makes it dramatically cheaper to operate at scale — log content is stored compressed in object storage, and search uses label-based filtering first. Elasticsearch indexes everything, which gives faster full-text search but at much higher infrastructure cost. For our use case — operational logs with structured labels like server name and severity — Loki's approach was a better fit.

### Q5: What is observability?

> Observability is the ability to understand the internal state of a system from its outputs. It has three pillars — logs (discrete events), metrics (numerical measurements over time), and traces (request flows through distributed systems). Monitoring tells you something is wrong; observability lets you figure out why.

### Q6: How did you implement role-based dashboards?

> Two layers. First, at the Grafana team/user level — users were assigned to teams (Plant Engineers, Plant Managers, Admins) with different permissions. Second, at the dashboard level — separate dashboards for each role with appropriate panels and access control. Plant engineers saw operational details (raw logs, server CPU/memory, error counts). Managers saw aggregated KPIs and trends without exposing raw operational data they didn't need.

### Q7: How did plant-specific filtering work?

> Used Grafana dashboard variables. Each dashboard had a `$plant` variable that populated a dropdown of available plants. All panel queries referenced this variable — for example, the error rate panel queried `errors{plant=$plant}`. One dashboard, dynamic plant selection. Cleaner than maintaining a dashboard per plant.

### Q8: How did the alerting work?

> Grafana's built-in alerting. Set up alert rules on specific queries — for example, "alert if error rate over the last 5 minutes exceeds 50 per minute" or "alert if a critical keyword appears in logs". Alerts were grouped to avoid noise and routed to appropriate teams via email and Slack. Severity levels (info, warning, critical) determined who got notified and how urgently.

### Q9: What's the difference between logs, metrics, and traces?

> Different data types for different purposes. Logs are discrete events — what happened, when, where. Used for debugging specific incidents. Metrics are numerical measurements over time — CPU, memory, request rate. Used for monitoring trends and triggering alerts. Traces are end-to-end request flows through distributed systems — used to understand performance and failures across services. Modern observability needs all three.

### Q10: What's a time-series database?

> A database optimized for time-series data — values indexed by timestamp. They handle high write rates, are append-only, and have efficient time-based queries. Prometheus is one example. The data model is typically tuples of (timestamp, metric name, labels, value). Operations like "rate over last 5 minutes" are first-class.

### Q11: What were the challenges?

> A few. First, log volume — some servers produced a lot of logs, indexing everything would have been expensive. Loki's label-based indexing helped manage this. Second, defining useful alerts without alert fatigue — needed to iterate on thresholds based on actual operational patterns. Third, getting plant-specific filtering right without duplicating dashboards — solved with Grafana variables. Fourth, ensuring secure role separation — making sure operational details weren't accidentally exposed in manager dashboards.

### Q12: How would you improve this further?

> A few directions. Add distributed tracing (Tempo or Jaeger) so we can see request flows across services. Add anomaly detection on top of static thresholds — current alerts are rule-based, but ML-based anomaly detection would catch unusual patterns proactively. Standardize log formats across servers (structured JSON logs) for easier parsing and filtering. Add SLO-based alerting — define service level objectives and alert when burn rate threatens them. Migrate from SQL Server to a proper time-series DB (Mimir or InfluxDB) if metrics volume grows. Add on-call rotation integration with PagerDuty.

